{[%evp 0,71,18,17,33,33,35,33,45,52,52,53,53,50,50,44,42,31,39,20,39,31,35,37,
43,43,67,73,73,61,68,41,54,45,64,57,71,66,91,75,80,86,86,82,63,45,68,68,50,51,
43,43,50,56,110,64,80,40,66,-74,-63,-77,-77,-111,-64,-127,-170,-145,-153,-175,
-141,-154,-157,-186]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 {A little bit
of a passive variation that is not very popular on the high level. Black tries
to finish the development slowly. I guess it makes sense in blitz games since
the next few Black moves can be played by hand. That being said, White keeps
control over the central squares which promises a long term advantage. Black's
idea is to exchange his light-squared bishop for one of the White's knights
and then to play c6, reaching a "c6 + e6 against "d4" structure.} (4... Nf6 $6
{A little bit of a weird move played a few times by Rapport.} 5. Nxf6+ ({
White can also play} 5. Bd3 Nbd7 6. Nf3 {which is a transposition to the main
line of the Rubinstein variation.}) 5... gxf6 {Black creates double pawns
without much necessity. Truth be told, I don't understand such an idea. Maybe
there is some comparison with the Caro-Kann variation 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3
dxe4 4.Nxe4 where 4...Nf6 5.Nxf6+ gxf6 is not very popular but still played
from time to time.} ({After} 5... Qxf6 6. Nf3 {Black will need to spend more
tempi to protect the queen. For example:} b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 $2 8. Bg5 Bxf3 9. Qd2
$1 Qxd4 10. Bb5+ {is a well-known trap from the kid's book.}) 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3
(7. Bf4 $6 e5 $5 {was slightly inaccurate and was played in the game Caruana
-Rapport, Wijk aan Zee 2014} 8. dxe5 $140 Qe7) 7... b6 8. g3 Qd7 9. Qe2 (9. Bg2
Ba6) 9... Bb7 10. Bg2 O-O-O 11. O-O h5 12. c4 {White is just better because of
the pawn structure.}) 5. Nf3 {Natural development is always good when you meet
some rare variation.} ({I tried some other options, like} 5. c4 {but here after
} Nf6 $1 (5... Bc6 $140 $6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Be3 {White's chances seems preferable
to me}) 6. Nxf6+ (6. Nc3 c5 $132) 6... Qxf6 7. Nf3 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2
O-O {I think Black is fine.}) 5... Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 {[#]} (6... Be7 {is an
interesting sideline but White can play} 7. Neg5 $1 {[%cal Yc6f3] Trying to
force Bxf3} Nd7 ({the natural} 7... h6 $4 {loses due to} 8. Nxf7 $1 $18) 8. Qe2
Bxf3 (8... Bd5 {was tried by G. Meier, but failed to impress} 9. c4 Bxf3 10.
Nxf3 Ngf6 11. O-O O-O 12. b3 c6 13. Bb2 {Black's position is solid but very
passive. Dominguez won convincingly 1-0 (37) Dominguez Perez, L (2739)-Meier,
G (2628) chess.com INT 2018}) 9. Nxf3 Ngf6 10. O-O O-O 11. c4 Re8 12. b3 c5 13.
Bb2 $14 {1-0 (65) Leko,P (2678) -Vaganian,R (2562) Biel 2017}) 7. Bf4 $5 {
I decided to recommend this move, but White has a pleasant choice here. Pick
the one according to your playstyle.} ({Probably I like} 7. c4 {less because
after} Ngf6 8. Nc3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 c5 10. d5 Ne5 11. Qe2 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 exd5 13.
cxd5 Bd6 14. Bg5 O-O 15. O-O-O {the position became double-edged since both
kings castled to the opposite sides.}) ({The most natural is} 7. O-O Ngf6 (7...
Bxe4 8. Bxe4 c6 {1-0 (41) Zhigalko,A (2580)-Rozentalis,E (2606) Tromsoe 2014})
8. Ng3 {Here the modern way to play with Black is} g6 $5 9. b3 Bg7 10. Ba3 Bf8
11. Bb2 Bg7 12. c4 O-O 13. b4 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 c6 15. a4 {The position reminds a
lot the Schlechter Variation from the Slav Defence. White has a pair of
bishops and more space, but Black has no weaknesses. Long manoeuvring play is
required}) (7. Qe2 $5 Ngf6 (7... Be7) 8. Neg5 {White tries to force Bxf3 like
in the previous line, but here the knight on f3 would stand better than on g3.
I think critical is} Qe7 $5 9. O-O (9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7) 9... h6 10. Ne4
Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Bxe4 12. Qxe4 c6 13. Bf4 Nf6 14. Qe2 Qd8 ({After} 14... g6 15. c4
Bg7 16. Qe3 {[%cal Gf4h6] Black still has problems to finish the development})
15. c4 Bd6 16. Ne5 O-O 17. Rad1 $14 {[%cal Gd1d3,Gd3g3] White's pieces look
more active. Now White does not any have a long-term advantage like a pair of
bishops. But the active plans Rd1-d3-g3 is possible. Black still needs to play
carefully to neutralize White's initiative.}) 7... Ngf6 ({It does not seem
very logical to give White the pair of bishops for free with} 7... Bxe4 8. Bxe4
c6 9. O-O Ngf6 10. Bd3 Be7 {Black's position is solid but without any active
play. A model game how to play with White can be:} 11. Qe2 O-O 12. Rfd1 Re8 13.
c4 {[#] Black does not want to open the position with c6-c5 because White has
the pair of bishop, but staying passively is also not the best idea.} a5 14.
Bc2 g6 15. h3 Qb6 16. Rd2 a4 17. Rad1 a3 18. b3 Qa5 19. g4 Rad8 20. Ne5 Qa8 21.
h4 Qc8 22. h5 Nxe5 23. dxe5 Rxd2 24. Bxd2 Nd7 25. Kg2 Rd8 26. hxg6 fxg6 27. f4
Nf8 28. Rf1 Rd7 29. b4 b5 30. c5 Rd4 31. Bb3 Qd7 32. Bc3 Rd3 33. Rf3 Rxf3 34.
Qxf3 Kf7 35. Kf2 Ke8 36. Ke2 Kd8 37. Bd2 Kc7 38. Bc2 Qd4 39. Qxa3 Kb7 40. Qf3
Qc4+ 41. Bd3 {1-0 (41) Zhigalko,A (2580)-Rozentalis,E (2606) Tromsoe 2014}) (
7... Be7 8. O-O Ngf6 9. Nxf6+ Bxf6 10. c3 O-O 11. Re1 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 c6 {
[#] seems OK for Black because he exchanged one pair of knights. But it still
looks more pleasant for White. Similar structures you can learn from the
Caro-Kann or Scandinavian.}) 8. Nxf6+ Nxf6 ({After} 8... Qxf6 9. Bxc7 {Black
loses a pawn which was one of the points behind 7.Bf4.}) 9. O-O ({Now and
later White can play} 9. c3 {which is a transposition to Negi's recommendation
from his book. But I think White can save a tempo on such a move.}) 9... Bxf3 {
Black should make this move before White goes Ne5.} 10. Qxf3 c6 {We should
discuss this structure here. It can be reached via many different move orders.
Black exchanges his "bad" bishop and puts his pawns on the light squares. His
idea is to strike in the centre with c5 or e5 at an appropriate moment or to
put pressure on d4 first. Black's position remains super solid but really
passive. As we already discussed White has two possible plans: 1.Defend d4
with c3 and try to put pressure and win space on both flanks. 2.Play c4
threatening to open the position with d5 on some variations.} 11. Be5 Bd6 12.
Rad1 {It's more pleasant to play with White here. If Black will exchange on e5
then White can take control over the d-file by using the d6-square for the
rook. If Black does not exchange then White could improve his position with
Re1 and c4 or force the exchange after Qg3. Conclusion: 4... Bd7 is a playable
line, but White easily achieves a risk-free advantage.} *

