{[%evp 0,80,30,43,30,26,26,43,50,49,59,59,47,49,50,49,35,35,35,35,31,34,37,34,
35,26,40,42,28,43,36,36,30,40,66,49,48,29,49,51,32,22,30,42,44,40,37,37,40,14,
4,-1,1,0,0,0,0,0,-24,-18,0,-25,-22,-22,-37,-37,-18,-8,-10,-18,0,-7,-6,-6,-4,0,
0,0,1,9,16,15,23]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 {This is a very
simple way of playing for Black. The arising structures are similar to the
Caro-Kann positions after 3.Nc3 dxe4. Black does not want to create many
weaknesses and hopes to slowly neutralize White's initiative. The advantage of
this line is that you can use it both against 3.Nc3 and 3.Nd2. In my youth,
back in 2001, I remember Anand during the KO World Championship played it with
success with Black, where a draw was an acceptable result for the tournament
strategy. Nowadays, however, this line is not so popular and played mainly by
Georg Meier. If you want to study this line for Black just check his games. In
general, it is super solid for Black, but many times you need to play
precisely to keep the balance. I guess if people want to play it safe then
there are easier options like the Petroff or the Berlin Defence. Meier
suffered many painful losses in this line, but it has not stopped him and he
came back with new improvements. Let's look a bit deeper:} 5. Nf3 (5. Bd3 {
is also interesting if you want to have more options with White} Ngf6 6. c3 $5
Nxe4 7. Bxe4 Nf6 8. Bc2 c5 9. Nf3 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bc5 11. O-O Bxd4 $140 12. cxd4
Bd7 13. a4 Bc6 14. Ra3 Nd5 15. Qg4 g6 16. Bh6 $36 {1/2 (32) Li,R (2548) -Meier,
G (2651) Saint Louis 2017}) 5... Ngf6 6. Bd3 {I recommend this move for White.}
({I remember I was trying to follow Anand's footsteps a few months later in
2002, but instead I ended up in a bad position very quickly} 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7.
c3 c5 8. Ne5 $5 {[#] At this moment it was a new idea for White and I
immediately made a mistake:} Nd7 $2 ({Correct was} 8... a6) 9. Bb5 Bd6 10. Qg4
{Kasparov, G -Ponomariov, R Linares 2002 Black cannot castle safely. I gave my
opponent a strong initiative for free. This is just an example of why Black
needs to be very careful from the get-go. Later during my career I did not
want to play this line with Black again even despite the fact that I found an
improvement.}) {Let's check the mainline first. If you like my idea with White
you can learn how to play against rare moves of Black in the next chapter.
Otherwise, consider something else with White on the 5th of 6th move.} 6... c5
7. O-O Nxe4 (7... cxd4 8. Qe2 Nxe4 9. Bxe4 {1-0 (40) Sethuraman,S (2617)
-Ledger, A (2361) Douglas ENG 2017}) 8. Bxe4 Nf6 9. Qe2 $5 {Here I suggest
quite a rare, but interesting idea. White's idea is to delay the development
of the c1 bishop and to clear the d1-square for the rook.} ({In 2014 Negi
published a nice book with a repertoire for White vs French and here he
recommended} 9. Bg5 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Be7 11. Bf3 O-O {Black's position looks
strategically risky. His main problem is that the knight on d4 is not defended.
White's plan is to play Rd1 and then to slowly advance his pawn majority on
the queenside.} 12. Qd3 {GM Georg Meier found a nice positional idea and
managed to neutralize White's pressure in the following game.} Bc5 $1 {
Removing the bishop from e7 with tempo and preparing e5.} (12... e5 $2 {
is premature due to} 13. Nf5 $16) 13. Rad1 e5 14. Nb3 Qxd3 15. cxd3 Bb6 16.
Rfe1 h6 17. Bh4 Be6 $1 18. Bg3 Rac8 19. Bxe5 Bxb3 20. axb3 Rc2 21. Rf1 Rd8 22.
Bxb7 Ng4 23. Bg3 Rxb2 {½- (40) ½ Vachier-Meier, Grenke Chess Classic, 2017
So that's why I started to look for something new to pose problems for Black.})
9... cxd4 (9... Nxe4 10. Qxe4 cxd4 11. Rd1 {is just a transposition to the
main line since Black cannot play} Bc5 {because of} 12. Qe5 {[%csl Gh5][%cal
Ge5c5,Ge5g7]}) 10. Rd1 {White is playing for quick development. Black is
forced to play many precise moves in this position whereas White's play is
natural and risk-free.} Nxe4 (10... Qb6 11. a4 $1 Bd7 12. a5 Qc7 13. a6 Nxe4
14. Qxe4 Bc6 15. Qxd4 {1-0 (50) Kotronias,V (2564)-Stupak,K (2494) Warsaw 2013}
) (10... Be7 {transposes to the main line 1-0 (40) Sethuraman,S (2617) -Ledger,
A (2361) Douglas ENG 2017}) 11. Qxe4 Be7 12. Rxd4 Qb6 {The opening stage is
almost finished. It is time to evaluate the position. Black has the bishop
pair, no weaknesses and is just one move away from castling. The drawback of
his position is that it is quite hard to develop the queenside and the
position is quite passive. White has 2 different plans to develop the
initiative. 13.b3 was used by GM Kotronias to score two nice wins. I give
these games but suggest another idea 13.Ne5} 13. Ne5 $1 {where Black needs to
play very precisely which is always a task during the practical game.} (13. b3
$5 f6 (13... O-O 14. Be3 Bc5 15. Ng5 {White's position looks promising. I am
giving you the following game to illustrate White's ideas and the danger of
Black's position.} f5 16. Qe5 Qc6 17. Nxh7 Bxd4 18. Bxd4 Rf7 19. Ng5 Rd7 20.
Qe3 e5 21. Qxe5 Qg6 22. h4 b6 23. Re1 Bb7 24. c3 Rf8 25. Qf4 Bd5 26. Re5 Qd6
27. Qe3 Qg6 28. Qd3 Bb7 29. f3 Bd5 30. Qb5 Qc6 31. Qe2 Qg6 32. Qd3 Bb7 33. Ne6
Rf6 34. Nf4 Qf7 35. Qe3 Kf8 36. h5 Rdd6 37. Ng6+ Rxg6 38. hxg6 Rxg6 39. Qf4 Bc8
40. Qh4 Qd7 41. a4 Rh6 42. Qg5 Qc7 43. Rd5 Qh2+ 44. Kf2 {1-0 (44) Kotronias,V 
(2611) -Dambacher,M (2471) Maastricht 2008}) 14. Be3 e5 15. Ra4 Qd6 ({I guess
something like} 15... Qc7 {can be an improvement for Black.} 16. Bxa7 Bd7 17.
Rc4 Bc6 18. Qe3 b5 19. Bb6 Qb7 20. Rc3 Rc8 $44 {[#]} (20... O-O 21. Nd4)) 16.
Rxa7 Rxa7 17. Bxa7 O-O 18. Be3 Rd8 19. h4 Qc7 20. c4 Qd7 21. c5 Qd3 22. Qb4 Qd5
23. Qb6 Bg4 24. Nd2 f5 25. f3 f4 26. Bf2 Qxd2 27. fxg4 Qd5 28. Re1 Rc8 29. Kh2
e4 30. Rd1 Qc6 31. Qxc6 bxc6 32. Rd7 Kf7 33. Rd4 Bxc5 34. Rxe4 Bd6 35. Kg1 h6 {
1-0 (35) Kotronias,V (2552)-Nikolaidis,I (2559) Vrachati 2014}) 13... f6 ({If} 
13... O-O 14. Nc4 Qa6 15. Bf4 {Black has some problems with finishing the
development of the queenside. Meanwhile, White's play is pretty straight and
simple here:} b5 16. Nd6 Bd7 (16... Bxd6 17. Bxd6 Bb7 18. Qg4 f5 19. Qe2 $14 {
[%csl Rb7,Gd6,Rg8]}) {Here some fancy variations can happen just to illustrate
the difficulties to play with Black:} 17. Nxf7 $5 Bc6 18. Nh6+ gxh6 19. Qxe6+
Rf7 20. Be3 h5 (20... Qc8 21. Rg4+ Bg5 22. Qxc8+ Rxc8 23. h4 Bd7 24. Rg3 Rxc2
25. hxg5 Rg7 26. Rd1 hxg5 27. Bxa7 {with an extra pawn in the endgame.}) 21.
Rd7 Re8 $8 22. Bd4 Qc8 $8 23. Qe5 Bf6 $8 24. Qg3+ Kf8 $8 25. Bc5+ (25. Qd6+ Kg8
26. Rxf7 Bxd4) 25... Be7 (25... Ree7 26. Rxe7 Rxe7 27. Bxe7+ Bxe7 28. Qe3 $36 {
[%csl Ra7,Rf8,Rh5,Rh7][%cal Ga1e1]}) 26. Qe5 Kg8 27. Rxe7 Rexe7 28. Bxe7 Qg4
29. Qg5+ (29. Qb8+ Kg7 30. Qe5+ Kg8) (29. f3 Bxf3 30. Qg5+ Rg7 31. Qxg4 Rxg4
32. g3 Re4) 29... Qxg5 30. Bxg5 Rg7 31. h4 h6 32. Bxh6 Rxg2+ 33. Kf1 Rh2 34.
Ke2 Rxh4 $14 {I guess with opposite coloured bishops a draw is the probable
result here, but Black needed to be very careful before to get here.}) 14. Nc4
Qa6 15. Bf4 e5 16. Bxe5 $1 {It is difficult to call this a real sacrifice
since it is very logical to play like this when Black's king is in the centre.}
fxe5 17. Qxe5 Qe6 $8 18. Qxg7 Rg8 19. Qxh7 Qg6 {Black needs to exchange the
queens otherwise White would just be attacking for free.} 20. Nd6+ Bxd6 (20...
Kf8 21. Rf4+ Bf6 22. Qxg6 Rxg6 23. Ne4 Kg7 24. Nxf6 Rxf6 25. Rxf6 Kxf6 26. Rd1
Bf5 27. Rd2 $14 {I do not know how big the chances for White are here, but
with 4 pawns vs. bishop only White can play for a win.}) 21. Re1+ Be6 {[#]} 22.
Rxe6+ $5 {This is not a winning move, but from a practical point of view, it
obliges Black to continue playing precisely} (22. Qxg6+ Rxg6 23. Rxd6 Ke7 {
With four rooks I guess it is easier for Black to hold White's passed pawns.})
22... Qxe6 23. Re4 Be5 24. Qh5+ Kd8 (24... Kd7 25. Rxe5 Qf6 26. Qh7+ Kd6 27. f4
Rae8 28. Qd3+ Kc7 29. Qc3+ Qc6 30. Rc5 Rxg2+ 31. Kf1 Rxh2 32. Rxc6+ bxc6 33. f5
) 25. Rxe5 Qg4 (25... Qf6 26. Rf5 Qe7 27. h3 Re8 28. Rc5) 26. Rd5+ Ke7 $8 27.
Qe5+ Kf7 28. Qc7+ Kf8 29. Qc5+ Kf7 $11 {Well, in the end, White needed to
accept a draw. I guess such is modern chess with engine analysis and we need
to find new ideas after this line will be played to surprise our opponent
again. But I do not mind taking my chances with White here. Conclusion: I
believe that White has good chances to obtain an advantage against the main
line of the Rubinstein Variation. White's position is quite active and Black
needs to play with extreme care not to end up in a very bad position.} *

