recent strong GM games was} h6 12. Qe3 (12. Ne5 $5) 12... Qb6 13. Rhe1 c5 14.
Qa3 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Qa4+ Bd7 17. Qxd4 Qxd4 18. Rxd4 O-O-O 19. Rb4 b6 20.
a4 Kc7 21. Re3 {and even this endgame was unpleasant for Black. 1-0 (37) So, W
(2773)-Bareev,E (2675) Chess Supersite INT 2016}) 9. Bd3 {I like this move
more. White is ready to sacrifice a pawn, but Black will be far behind in the
development.} (9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. c3 {is also playable if White does not want to
sacrifice anything.} f5 (10... Bd7 11. Nd2 c6 (11... O-O-O 12. Qf3) 12. O-O
O-O-O 13. Nc4 Qf4 14. Re1 h5 15. a4 $14) 11. Bc2 Bd7 (11... Bg7 12. Qe2 O-O 13.
Rg1 $36 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gg2g4]}) 12. Qe2 O-O-O 13. Ne5 Be8 14. O-O Rg8 15.
Rad1 Kb8 16. Rfe1 $14 {looks better for White, but at least Black has a pair
of bishops.}) 9... Qb4+ 10. Bd2 Qxb2 11. O-O Be7 ({After} 11... Qa3 12. Ne5 Qd6
13. Bf4 Qd8 14. Qf3 {White had a dangerous initiative for the pawn. 1-0 (40)
Saric, I (2628)-Zatonskih, A (2471) Bastia 2013}) 12. c4 $5 {[#] White
obviously has compensation for the pawn. Nowadays almost nobody wants to go
here with Black. Compare this line with the Modern Vienna Gambit 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 e6 3.Nf3 d5 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.e4 Bb4 5.Bxc4 Nxe4 6.0-0 etc.} O-O {In 2012 I
prepared this line with my second Vladimir Baklan and planned to play} 13. Qe2
$5 {in case Wang Hao had repeated this line again.} (13. Re1 {This is the game
Karjakin - Wang Hao from the FIDE Grand-Prix in Tashkent 2012 where I played
myself. It's okay to play like this. In general, there is no rush for White.
His pieces are on nice squares and he can prepare some attack against Black's
king on the kingside. Meanwhile, Black still has some problems to finish the
development with the bishop on c8 and the rook on a8.} Qb6 14. Bc3 Qd6 15. Ne5
b5 $5 {Trying to return back material, but finally, develop pieces instead.} (
15... b6 16. Qf3 Bd7 17. g4 $1 {with a strong attack.}) (15... c5 16. dxc5 Qxc5
17. Re3 $5 {also gives White the initiative}) 16. c5 Qd5 17. Bxb5 Bb7 18. f3
Qd8 {Now White should play} 19. Rb1 $1 $14 {(Negi) and Black still has
problems to solve with the rooks.} ({Karjakin instead played} 19. Nc6 $2 {
which is positionally wrong because having less space Black is happy to
exchange some pieces.} Bxc6 20. Bxc6 Nd5 21. Qd3 Rb8 22. Qc4 Nxc3 23. Qxc3 Bf6
24. Rad1 g6 25. Qc4 Bg7 26. d5 exd5 27. Qxd5 Qf6 $15 {was even better for
Black because with opposite coloured bishops his king looks safer. Karjakin -
Wang Hao, Tashkent, 2012})) 13... c5 {Looks like a quite natural reaction, but
leads to problems for Black after:} ({The following lines are not really
necessary, but can be illustrative to demonstrate the spirit of the position.} 
13... Qa3 14. c5 $1 (14. Bf4 {is possible too} b6 15. Bxc7 Bb7 16. Rab1 Rac8
17. Rb3 Qa4 18. Be5 Rfd8 19. Rfb1 Ng4 20. Bf4 h6 $132 {The position is unclear,
but I believe that Black is doing fine.}) 14... Rd8 15. Rfb1 (15. Bc1 $5 {
Also leads to an advantage.} Qa5 16. a4 c6 17. Bd2 Qc7 18. a5 Bd7 19. Rab1 Nd5
20. Ne5 g6 21. Rfe1 $36) 15... Qa4 {It is obvious that White's compensation
for the pawn is overwhelming.} 16. Bb5 {I am giving you the following line
just to show you the typical ideas for White and the danger of Black's
position. The moves are not forced just illustrative.} Qc2 17. Rb3 Qe4 18. Re3
Qc2 19. Rc1 Qxa2 20. Qd1 Bd7 21. Bc4 Qa4 22. Bb3 Qb5 23. Rb1 Ng4 24. Rxe6 Bxe6
25. Bxe6 Nxf2 26. Kxf2 Qe8 27. Ba2 Bf6 28. Bf4 $36) 14. Rfb1 Qa3 15. Rb3 Qa4
16. dxc5 Qc6 17. Bc3 Qxc5 18. Rb5 {[#] Black's queen is not really safe here}
Qc7 (18... Qc6 {is well met by} 19. Rg5 g6 20. Qc2 Qe8 21. Re1 Bd7 22. Qc1 Rc8
23. Rg3 Rc5 24. Ne5 $16) 19. Be5 Qc6 20. Nd4 Qe8 21. Rb3 {I like White's
position a lot. Black is a pawn up, but cannot develop the queenside and will
be under attack on the kingside soon.} g6 22. Nb5 Qc6 23. Nc7 Rb8 24. Nd5 exd5
25. cxd5 Nxd5 26. Bxb8 Bf6 27. Re1 Nc3 28. Qf3 Qxf3 29. gxf3 Be6 30. Rxb7 Bd5
31. Rb2 $14 {Black needs to fight hard for a draw. Conclusion: The sidelines
on move 6 do not give Black equal chances. White keeps an upper hand in all
the lines.} *

