or less equal position.}) 13... Qa5+ 14. Qd2 Qxd2+ ({Actually at some moment
this line got my attention with Black because Garry Kasparov almost lost a
game here with White during the rapid match Russia vs. the World in 2002} 14...
Rd8 15. cxd5 $6 ({But correct was to play the simple} 15. Qxa5 $142 $1 Nxa5 16.
Rd1 $1 Nb8 ({If} 16... Nxc4 17. Bxc4 dxc4 18. Rd6 {[%csl Ra8,Rc8,Rd8] Black's
pieces are tied.}) 17. cxd5 exd5 18. Kf2 Nbc6 19. Nd4 Bd7 20. Be2 {White has a
really nice position. A possible line is:} Nc4 21. Nxc6 Bxc6 22. Bxc4 dxc4 23.
Rd6 {Even the opposite-coloured bishops do not really solve all of Black's
problems.}) 15... Qxd2+ 16. Bxd2 exd5 17. Rc1 Re8 18. Kf2 f6 19. e6 Rxe6 20.
Bd3 Re8 21. g4 Nf8 22. Rhg1 Bd7 {and White's compensation for the sacrificed
pawn was questionable. 1/2 (78) Kasparov,G (2838)-Radjabov,T (2610) Moscow 2002
}) 15. Kxd2 Rd8 16. Kc3 Ne7 17. Rb1 Nf8 {White's position looks nice, but
sometimes it is not so easy to break Black defence[#] After studying it deeply,
I found the following plan the most promising.} 18. Be2 $1 {To explain the
difference I will show some games where White failed to achieve an advantage
after 18.Bd3 or 18.Nd4. Black's key defensive idea is the manoeuvre Rd8-d7-c7
and only then Bd7. After that Black has several ideas: 1. dxc4 followed by Nd5
and (or) Bb5 2. Double the rooks on the c-file and put pressure on the c5 and
