J (2498) Budapest 2018}) (20... Rc8 21. Rb7 Bb4+ 22. Kf2 Qe7 (22... Qxb6 {
A very interesting and quite typical queen sacrifice for this line.} 23. Rxb6
Bc5 24. Rd1 (24. Qxc5 Rxc5 25. Rxa6) 24... O-O 25. Rxa6 $1 {And Black needs to
be very accurate. I believe that White keeps practical chances to convert his
small advantage.} (25. cxd5 $6 exd5 26. Rxa6 Bf5 27. Qxc5 Rxc5 28. Nd2 Rc2 29.
Kg3 $4 (29. h3 $11) 29... Bd3 $19 {0-1 (39) Svetushkin,D (2542)-Jianu,V (2523)
Satu Mare 2019})) (22... Qh4+ $2 {is a well known mistake.} 23. g3 Qh5 24. Rxd7
$3 Kxd7 25. c5 Bxc5 26. Bxc5 Rc6 27. Nd2 {White's advantage is obvious. ½-½ 
(42) Wagner,D (2568)-Stojanovic,M (2493) Baden 2017}) 23. Rc1 Bc5 24. Bxc5 Qxc5
25. Qxc5 Rxc5 26. Rb8+ Bc8 27. Rc3 $1 $14 {With an initiative for White.}) 21.
Nd2 $1 {I analyzed this line a bit before the tournament.} ({Unfortunately} 21.
O-O {is just a forced draw if Black plays all precise moves:} dxc4 22. Qf2 (22.
Nc3 {does not change much} Bb5) 22... Bb5 23. Nc3 O-O 24. a4 {[#]} Bb4 $1 25.
Na2 Bd2 26. axb5 Rxb6 $1 27. Qxb6 Qd3 28. Rf3 Qb1+ 29. Rf1 Qd3 30. Rf3 Qb1+ 31.
Rf1 Qd3 {1/2 Jakovenko, D -Lysyj, I Vladivostok 2014}) ({I actually planned to
try} 21. Nc3 {But I had not expected this concrete line from my opponent and
did not check my analysis before the game.} Bb4 $1 (21... dxc4 $2 {is bad} 22.
Rb7 $1 Rxb7 23. Bxd8 Bxd8 24. Ke2 Rb2+ 25. Kf3 Bc6+ 26. Ne4 $18 {looks good
for White}) 22. c5 O-O 23. O-O (23. Qxb4 Qxc7) 23... Bxc3 24. Qxc3 Bb5 25. Rd1
Qh4 26. Qd4 {Again I think that White's advantage is objectively small, but
the position is unpleasant to play for Black. White can push for a win without
any risk. 1/2 (72) Quesada Perez, Y -Espinosa Veloz, E Merida 2016}) 21... Bb4
$2 {My opponent started to think for the first time during the game and this
move already is a decisive mistake.} (21... O-O 22. cxd5 exd5 23. O-O Bf5 ({
I guess} 23... Qe8 $5 {[%cal Ge7d8] with the threat 24...Bd8 can be an
improvement for Black. All black pieces are on the last rank. But it is kind
of hard for White to not let Black activate his pieces.} 24. Bc5 Qd8 25. Bxe7
Qxc7 26. Bxf8 Rxf8 {The positon should be around equal, but strategically
risky for Black.}) 24. Nb3 Ba3 25. Rb7 Qc8 26. Rc7 Qd8 27. h3 Qh4 28. Kh2 {
was better for White in the game 1/2 (59) Leko, P -Nakamura, H Zug 2013}) 22.
c5 $2 {It was like hypnosis for both of us during the game. I was probably
thinking that I am following my analysis with 21.Nc3 where 22.c5 is correct.} (
{But here just winning is} 22. cxd5 $1 Bxd2+ 23. Kxd2 exd5 {but I missed} 24.
e6 $1 Bxe6 25. Qxg7 Rf8 26. Qd4 {and White just has an attack for free.}) 22...
Rc8 $1 (22... Bxd2+ 23. Kxd2 O-O 24. c6 $18) 23. Ra7 ({Unfortunatelly not
working for me was} 23. Qxb4 Rxc7 24. Qa5 Qh4+ 25. g3 Qg4 26. Bxc7 Bb5 {
[%csl Re1] and with an extra knight I cannot protect my king}) ({Probably
better was} 23. Rxc8 Bxd2+ 24. Kxd2 Qxc8 25. c6 $5 Qxc6 26. Rc1 Qb5 27. Bc5 {
with some initiative for the pawn}) 23... Qh4+ 24. g3 Qh3 $4 {For some reason
my opponent now was in time trouble. But the long thought was
counterproductive.} ({After} 24... Bxd2+ 25. Qxd2 Qg4 {the position is
absolutely unclear because the white king is also weak.}) 25. Qxb4 Qg2 26. Rf1
Bb5 27. Rf2 Qg1+ 28. Nf1 Bxf1 29. c6 $1 {Probably missed by my opponent. Now
my rook is protected by the bishop and I am threating mate in one. 1-0
Ponomariov-Filip, Skopje, 2019} (29. Rxf1 $2 Qe3+ 30. Kd1 Qd3+ 31. Ke1 Qe3+ $11
{It was a badly played game. But I hope the reader received some feeling about
this variation. Conclusion: The lines with 7...Qb6 or cxd4 followed by Qb6 is
tricky and very ambitious. The white player should study them carefully and
remember some long and forced lines. I cannot claim an indisputable advantage
for White in all the lines, but in the worst case he can put pressure in
risk-free positions for a long time.}) *

