{[%evp 0,14,25,28,25,25,33,26,15,20,18,13,19,19,36,8,46] Let's take a look at
this chapter some moves that are not very frequently played, but may catch you
sometimes as a surprise} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6.
Nf3 Nc6 ({A very interesting position arises after} 6... Be7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2
a6 $5 {[#] Black opts for a very tricky move order. As we are going to see,
keeping the knight on b8 gives Black some flexibility. Now I suggest} 9. Be2 $5
({Black's point can be seen after} 9. dxc5 Nxc5 10. O-O-O Nbd7 $1 {and things
are not so clear with opposite castled kings. Now White does not have the
attacking plan with Bd3 because Black can always exchange this bishop.}) 9...
b5 10. O-O b4 {This pawn expansion seems to be a bit premature since Black's
development is not good enough to sustain his space advantage,} ({The move} 
10... Nc6 {which is transposing to my game versus Dominguez is dealt with in
Chapter 11.}) 11. Na4 c4 12. c3 Nc6 13. b3 $1 {This is the point. Being better
developed, White is interested in opening up the position.} cxb3 14. axb3 bxc3
15. Qxc3 Nb4 16. Rfc1 a5 17. Bd2 Ba6 18. Bxa6 Rxa6 19. Qc7 {White's advantage
is obvious.}) 7. Be3 a6 (7... Rb8 {[#] With a similar idea to prepare some
play on the queenside by saving a tempo on ...a7-a6. Black is planning to
follow with ...Qa5 and ...b7-b5. I think there is nothing wrong to play simply}
8. Be2 $5 {and just to finish the development.} ({More popular is} 8. Qd2 {
but it's also more complicated after} Qa5) {Now, if Black will insist too much
on the queenside by playing} 8... Qa5 9. O-O b5 {White has a strong reaction -}
10. a4 $1 b4 11. Nb5 a6 12. f5 {with a very dangerous initiative}) 8. Qd2 Qb6
9. O-O-O Qa5 $5 {This idea was found by my friend and second GM Vladimir
Baklan back in 2013. Black is losing a tempo but forcing White to castle long.
Meanwhile, Black's king is more flexible and depending on the circumstances
can castle long or short. But a tempo is always a tempo.} 10. dxc5 {The most
natural answer} ({In case of} 10. Kb1 $6 {Black can fully justify his idea:} c4
11. Qf2 b5 12. f5 b4 {Black's attack develops faster} 13. fxe6 (13. Ne2 exf5
14. Ng5 Nb6) 13... bxc3 14. Ng5 (14. exd7+ Bxd7) 14... Nf6 $1 $19) (10. f5 $5
cxd4 11. Bxd4 Bb4 12. fxe6 fxe6 13. a3 Nxd4 14. axb4 Nxf3 15. gxf3 Qxb4 16. Rg1
{looks unclear. There is no real need for White to take extra risk.}) 10...
Bxc5 ({The obvious alternative is} 10... Nxc5 {when I suggest} 11. Kb1 (11. f5
Na4 $13) 11... b5 12. Ne2 $5 $146 {Probably the most safest} Qxd2 13. Nxd2 h5
14. Nc1 Bd7 15. Ncb3 {White's position is more pleasant.}) 11. Bxc5 ({On} 11.
Kb1 Bb4 {looks annoying}) 11... Nxc5 12. Qe3 $5 {with the typical idea to slow
down the advance ...b7-b5-b4.} Na4 ({The move} 12... Ne7 {allows} 13. Nd4) ({
On the other hand} 12... O-O 13. Kb1) ({and} 12... Bd7 13. Kb1 {are quite
similar.}) 13. Nxa4 Qxa4 14. a3 Bd7 (14... b5 15. c3 {[%csl Ra4]}) 15. Bd3 Qa5
({In general,} 15... b5 {is always well met by} 16. c3) 16. Kb1 h6 17. h4 O-O-O
18. Rh3 {[%csl Gd3,Rd7] White has a typical long term advantage thanks to the
pawn structure and his better bishop.} *

