{[%evp 0,95,19,38,30,45,34,45,39,30,46,2,12,18,25,40,41,11,21,9,25,1,12,18,14,
10,18,12,50,57,32,1,26,3,-2,-43,-8,-33,-8,-36,-1,1,20,21,14,27,23,6,22,7,14,16,
31,23,25,20,56,39,70,75,80,46,67,67,82,82,87,97,87,97,136,121,137,109,119,132,
123,126,133,127,217,198,222,228,215,209,256,212,224,233,254,268,259,244,251,
190,337,408]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7.
Be3 a6 8. Qd2 b5 {[#] This is by far the most popular move. Black is expanding
on the queenside. So, for White is already really dangerous to castle long.
Here my suggestion is} 9. Be2 {Probably this is the critical position of the
opening. After many years, I am still trying to figure out what's the best
move for White since he has many options. I will try to briefly explain why I
prefer the move 9.Be2 over the alternatives.} (9. a3 {is a classical move to
prevent b5-b4. But during one of the World Cup matches I had troubles to prove
some advantage for White after} Qa5 {trying to play b5-b4 anyway} 10. dxc5 Bxc5
11. Bxc5 Nxc5 12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Na4 14. b4 Qb6 15. Qxb6 Nxb6 {I didn't
manage to create problems for Black in this endgame, even despite the fact
that White visually looks better due to his superior bishop. The game went} 16.
Bd3 Bd7 17. Ne2 h5 18. Nd4 g6 19. g3 Ke7 20. Kd2 Rac8 21. h3 Rh6 22. Raf1 Rg8
23. Ke3 Rc8 24. Rhg1 Rhh8 25. Nb3 Na4 26. Kd4 Rc7 27. Rf2 Rcc8 {At least I was
already leading in the match and draw was not such a terrible result for me. 1/
2 (49) Ponomariov, R -Akobian, V Khanty Mansiysk 2009}) ({Later I tried to
follow Negi's recommendation from his book} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Bd3 Qb6 11. Bf2 {
But now theory developed and Black started playing the tricky} h6 $5 ({One of
my blitz games went} 11... O-O 12. a3 ({In the book, it was recommended} 12.
O-O Bxf2+ 13. Rxf2 Bb7 14. a3 {which can be a transposition}) 12... f6 13. exf6
Rxf6 14. O-O Bxf2+ 15. Rxf2 Bb7 16. Re1 Raf8 17. g3 h6 {with a complex
position. Nevertheless, I was not really happy with the final result 0-1 (64)
Ponomariov,R -Ponkratov,P Berlin 2015}) 12. O-O Bb7 13. a3 Bxf2+ 14. Rxf2 Nc5
$132 {Since Black has not castled yet. White does not have such a direct and
comfortable attack as it was promised in the book.}) (9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O O-O
11. a3 {can be a transposition to the game Cheparinov-Bluebaum that I
mentioned in my annotations to the game with Lenier Dominguez.}) (9. Nd1 $5 {
Can be in the spirit of my current game. I played it after 9.Be2}) 9... Bb7 {
[#]} ({Later at the same tournament when we played blitz section my opponent
tried to improve with} 9... Qb6 10. Nd1 cxd4 ({Sometimes, Black tries to
further expand on the queenside by means of} 10... b4 {planning ...a6-a5
followed by ...Ba6. In this case, I think that White should stabilize the
centre by playing} 11. c3 a5 ({Black is not ready to open the centre with} 
11... bxc3 {when after} 12. Nxc3 Rb8 13. b3 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gc3a4] he should
reckon with the idea of Rc1 followed by Na4. In general, White is trying to
provoke ...cxd4, thus gaining control of the d4-square and the weakened c-file.
} Qa5 14. Rc1 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 {White was better in 1-0 (32)
Grischuk,A (2746)-Potkin,V (2682) Khanty-Mansiysk 2011}) 12. O-O Be7 {Black
takes care of the development before going for ...Ba6.} ({The immediate} 12...
Ba6 {is well met by} 13. Bxa6 Qxa6 ({After} 13... Rxa6 14. f5 {the ideas are
similar.}) 14. f5 exf5 15. Bf4 $1 {This is the point. Now White is ready to
attack the weak pawns with Ne3. The following game is very instructive:} bxc3
16. Nxc3 Nb6 17. a4 Nd8 18. Nb5 Ne6 19. Ng5 Qc8 20. g4 fxg4 21. Be3 Nxg5 22.
Bxg5 Qd7 23. Rae1 Nc8 24. Qf4 {1-0 (24) Harikrishna,P (2737)-Studer,N (2493)
Biel 2017}) 13. Bf2 {[%cal Gd1e3] A typical move in such positions. With his
last move, White frees the e3-square which is perfect for his knight.} Ba6 ({
In case of} 13... O-O {White could opt for the immediate} 14. f5 {A
high-profile game continued} bxc3 15. bxc3 cxd4 16. cxd4 Ba6 17. Bxa6 Qxa6 18.
Ne3 Bb4 19. Qd1 $36 {when White has very good attacking chances on the
kingside. A possible idea would be Ng5 followed by the queen transfer to the
kingside. 0-1 (38) Svidler,P (2735)-Morozevich,A (2741) Monte Carlo 2005}) ({
The attempt to slow down White kingside attack by} 13... g6 {runs into the
typical} 14. c4 $1 {You should always consider this break when ...dxc4 can be
met with d4-d5.} dxc4 $2 {Of course, allowing d4-d5 is not advisable.} ({
Nevertheless, even the more precise} 14... cxd4 {leaves Black in a
strategically difficult position after} 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Bxd4
Bc5 18. Bf2 $16) 15. d5 exd5 16. Ne3 d4 {0-1 (38) Barrientos Chavarriaga,S 
(2500)-Buchenau, F (2299) Badalona 2012. And now White should have played} 17.
Nxc4 Qd8 18. f5 $18 {with a winning attack.}) 14. Bxa6 Qxa6 15. f5 a4 $2 {
Keeping the king in the centre and following with the queenside play is a
rather risky strategy.} ({Black should have played} 15... O-O {but even then,
after} 16. Ne3 {White's position is easier.}) 16. Ng5 h6 17. fxe6 Bxg5 18.
exd7+ Kxd7 19. Be3 $18 {1-0 (33) Andriasian,Z (2603)-Meier,G (2639) chess.com
INT 2018}) 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 {This seems to be the most precise move order.} ({
Delaying the exchange of the knights with} 11... Bc5 12. c3 Bb7 {gives White
the option of playing} 13. b4 {which gives White the bishop pair and a strong
center.} Bxd4 14. cxd4 a5 $2 {1/2 (42) Souleidis,G (2429)-Zumsande,M (2413)
Germany 2009} ({Preferable was} 14... O-O {when White should probably consider
playing on both wings with} 15. a4 bxa4 16. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Gc3a4]}) {At this
point, the precise} 15. f5 $1 {gives White a huge advantage.} exf5 (15... axb4
16. fxe6 fxe6 17. O-O $16 {[%csl Re6,Re8][%cal Ge2g4]}) 16. Nc3 $16) 12. Bxd4
Bc5 13. c3 b4 (13... O-O 14. O-O a5 15. Ne3 b4 16. Bg4 {Leads to a
transposition.}) 14. O-O a5 15. Bg4 $5 {keeping more tension in the position.}
O-O 16. Ne3 Ba6 17. Rfe1 {I think I got a nice position anyway with chances
for an attack on the kingside. Later typical blitz play with blunders started}
g6 $2 18. Nxd5 exd5 19. Bxd7 $16 {etc. 0-1 (43) Ponomariov, R -Wang, H Huaian
2016}) (9... Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 ({But white can also try to play} 11. Nd1
$5 b4 12. c3 a5 13. Bf2 f6 (13... f5 $6 14. c4) (13... Ba6 14. Bxa6 Rxa6 15.
Ne3 c4 16. f5 a4 17. a3 bxc3 18. bxc3 Na5 19. Qc2 $36 {[%csl Rg8]}) 14. Ne3
fxe5 15. dxe5 {with a complex play}) 11... Bb7 {can be a transposition to my
game vs. Dominguez}) 10. Nd1 $5 {Since White cannot do much it makes sense to
concentrate more pieces on the kingside. I was a bit inspired by the victory
of my friend Alexander Areschenko against Wang Hao in 2015 at the Romanian
league. In that game, Black played ...b7-b6 and ...Bc8-b7. One year later,
Wang Hao versus me decided to expand more on the queenside which I think is a
better idea.} b4 11. O-O Qb6 12. Nf2 ({It can be actually a better idea to
keep the pawn chain intact with} 12. c3 $5 {Later on, White can follow with
the typical Bf2 followed by Ne3. It is important to know that direct play
doesn't make Black's life easier. For example:} bxc3 13. bxc3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Bb4
15. Qc2 Rc8 16. Rb1 Qa5 17. Qb3 {and after all these active moves, Black
pieces should return back.}) 12... cxd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bc5 15. c3 Rc8
16. Rfe1 a5 17. Bg4 {This position can be okay for Black. Nevertheless, it's
still easier to play with White since Black's king doesn't feel safe.} g6 ({
I was planning to answer} 17... O-O {with} 18. f5) 18. Bf3 h5 19. Rad1 bxc3 {
My opponent decided to exchange queens to simplify the position a bit. But it
didn't solve all problems.} ({Probably better it was to wait with} 19... Kf8 {
[%cal Gf8g7]}) 20. bxc3 Bxd4 21. cxd4 Qb4 22. Qxb4 $5 ({It was possible to play
} 22. Qe3 Rc3 $140 23. Rd3 {But since it was a rapid game, playing simple
chess can be not so bad idea.}) 22... axb4 23. Rd2 Ke7 24. Rb1 Ba6 25. Rxb4
Rc1+ 26. Nd1 Rb8 27. Rbb2 Bc4 28. Kf2 Rxb2 29. Rxb2 Ra1 30. Nc3 Rc1 31. Nd1 Ra1
32. Ne3 $1 {After some move repetition, I realized that I can save my extra
pawn} Bd3 (32... Rxa2 33. Nxc4 Rxb2+ 34. Nxb2) (32... Bxa2 33. Nc2) 33. Be2 {
Now White is technically winning. The rest was a matter of technique.} Be4 34.
Nd1 Kd8 35. Nc3 Bf5 36. Ke3 f6 37. a4 fxe5 38. fxe5 Kc7 39. Ra2 Rh1 40. h3 Rc1
41. Nb5+ Kb8 42. a5 h4 43. a6 Nb6 44. a7+ Ka8 45. Ra6 Nc4+ 46. Bxc4 Rxc4 47.
Kf4 Bd3 48. Rxe6 {1-0 Ponomariov-Wang Hao, Huainan, 2016} *

