{[%evp 0,14,25,28,25,25,33,26,15,20,18,13,19,19,36,8,46]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3.
Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 {A very interesting position arises after}
Be7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 a6 $5 {[#] Black opts for a very tricky move order. As
we are going to see, keeping the knight on b8 gives Black some flexibility.
Now I suggest} 9. Be2 $5 b5 10. O-O Nc6 11. a3 {This is a subtle positional
move. White is preparing to play Rad1 followed by dxc5. Afterwards, he can
occupy the d4-square with a piece.} ({After the immediate} 11. Rad1 {White
should reckon with} b4 {when the d1-square is no longer available for the
knight.}) ({Another typical approach to the position is} 11. Nd1 {White is
planning to transfer the knight to the kingside and stabilize the centre with
c2-c3.}) 11... Bb7 {Now Black does not have counterplay with f7-f6 and I was a
bit sad that my quick preparation for the game didn't really work as I wanted.}
(11... Qb6 12. Rad1 Bb7 {transposes to the game.}) 12. Rad1 Rc8 {Looks like a
natural move. Nevertheless, I am not so sure that this is the best approach.
In general, my experience here with Black is not so big and I am still trying
to figure out what's the best plan here.} ({Later I saw that in correspondence
chess people actually preferred} 12... Qb6 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Bxc5 Nxc5 15. Qe3
Rac8 {which can be a better idea. Is the slightly passive b7-bishop such a big
deal? Of course, White can opt for} 16. Bd3 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2d4] followed by
Ne2-d4. In this case, his play is a bit easier.}) 13. dxc5 Nxc5 (13... Bxc5 $5
14. Bxc5 Nxc5 {was similar to 12...Qb6}) 14. Nd4 {In order to carry out the
advance f4-f5, White should eliminate the pressure on the e5-pawn. The idea
behind 14.Nd4 is to stabilize the centre by playing Nxc6 followed by Bd4.} Qc7
15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. Bd4 Ne4 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Qe3 {[#] In fact, I didn't play so
badly in China. After first two days, I was sharing 3rd place in the rapid
section. But this was just not my day.} Qxc2 $4 ({I didn't like that the
position is static with no visible counterplay for Black. For example:} 18...
a5 19. c3 b4 20. axb4 axb4 21. c4 {It reminded me of my own game with Bluebaum.
But it was not necessary to lose just in one move.}) 19. Rc1 Qa4 {When my
opponent started to think after 18...Qc2 I realized that I blundered} 20. b4 $1
{my queen is trapped and I can't do anything about it. Don't rush even when
you have just 15 minutes for the whole game!} Bd5 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 22. Bd1 Rc2 23.
Bxc2 Qxc2 24. Rc1 Qd3 25. Rc8+ Bf8 26. Qxd3 exd3 27. Bc5 {1-0 (27) Dominguez
Perez,L (2752)-Ponomariov,R (2682) Hengshui, CHN 2019.} *

